    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Deaniacs' Did Just Fine</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nancy Walker Koppelman letter holds that Robert Hicks made some excellent points in his Jan 7 Op-Ed article, but criticizes him for taking swipe at Democratic National Committee chmn Howard Dean</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Robert Hicks made some excellent points in ''An Election With No Losers'' (Op-Ed, Jan. 7). But why did he find it necessary, as so many do, to take a swipe at former Gov. Howard Dean, the chairman of the Democratic National Committee? What is the ''reflexive Deaniac liberalism'' that he claims has run the party amok?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Robert Hicks made some excellent points in ''An Election With No Losers'' (Op-Ed, Jan. 7). But why did he find it necessary, as so many do, to take a swipe at former Gov. Howard Dean, the chairman of the Democratic National Committee? What is the ''reflexive Deaniac liberalism'' that he claims has run the party amok?</p>
        <p>If it brought the party its successful 50-state strategy, refocused this nation on the unsuccessful Iraq war, and revitalized the grass-roots supporters who helped carry the Democratic Party to an overwhelming victory in November, then I believe that this ''reflexive Deaniac liberalism'' is working quite well.</p>
        <p>Nancy Walker Koppelman  Santa Barbara, Calif., Jan. 8, 2007</p>
      </block>
